[{'rating': 2, 'description': "Arrived with high expectations based on friends' recommendations, but our dining experience was mixed. The Bibibmyeon and Pork Rib stood out as delicious options, while the remaining dishes were merely average, and the portion sizes left much to be desired. The Pajeon was over fried and the Prawn Maggi goreng was overly salty.

When we shared this feedback to the 2 wait staff by our table, one of them kindly offered to remake the Maggi goreng, a gesture we appreciated but declined as we were already full. Unfortunately, the other staff member chose a less tactful / passive-aggressive approach by loudly asking the table next to ours if they liked their Maggi goreng, making their reply unmistakably audible to us. ‚ÄúYou mean it was not too salty? It was very good?‚Äù This came across as unnecessary and arrogant. Not cool.

We also found a $20 charge on for water for 4 of us. Not even sure if it was still/bottled or just tap water.", 'date': 'a week ago', 'images': ['https://storage.googleapis.com/synthesis_geos_public/thumbnails/thumb_unavail.jpg']}, {'rating': 3, 'description': 'I was really excited to try Tambi - but truthfully feel very unsatisfied after leaving.

The staff was nice, helpful, engaged with patrons and it was really fun to watch how each dish was put together - the atmosphere was energetic. We ended up waiting 15 minutes for our main when everything else had come in quick succession.

The food overall‚Ä¶it was just ok. I‚Äôm glad I tried it but I don‚Äôt think I‚Äôll be returning. Portions were tiny for the price point.
Nothing blew my mind, nothing made me want more. Some dishes had excessive salty seasonings (which I usually enjoy) but my tongue doesn‚Äôt feel great post-meal. Out of the dishes I tried, I enjoyed the Tambi bibimmyeon, the murtabak, and the sauce for the thosai panjeon.

The negroni was excellent üëåüèΩ

The slice of pie was flavourful and I love banana - but my crust tasted salty like it perhaps had touched some of the other food.', 'date': 'a week ago', 'images': ['https://storage.googleapis.com/synthesis_geos_public/thumbnails/thumb_unavail.jpg']}, {'rating': 5, 'description': "When I heard the good reviews about Tambi in late June, I quickly secured a reservation for mid Jul. And it wasn't disappointing at all.

Ordered 8/14 of the dishes on the current menu. My favourite was the beef tartare while my friend's was the cold buckwheat noodles. The weakest dish was the scallops as we simply had better scallops elsewhere.

Even though they are Indian-Korean fusion, I don't think any of the dishes tasted distinctly one way. Whether this is good or bad, I leave it for you to assess. By the way, at the time of this review (23/7/2023), they are fully booked up to end Sep 2023. The madness..", 'date': '2 months ago', 'images': ['https://storage.googleapis.com/synthesis_geos_public/thumbnails/thumb_unavail.jpg']}, {'rating': 2, 'description': 'Severely overhyped. Service was appalling and disappointing. Food was unimpressive and can be replaced by more affordable & better alternatives elsewhere. Although the idea of presenting Indian-Korean fusion food was promising and novel, Tambi failed to deliver.

Dine as a couple and was seated swiftly. It would be good if the service staff could have indicated where I can place my bulky bag somewhere. A group which arrived, seated and ordered after us, were served both alcohol and starters before us. Apparently, the staff forgot our order. I had to tell the drink staff that I ordered a cocktail before he proceeded the make one for me. They only started serving us our food after we reminded them that we have ordered. All these time, we were just looking at the groups beside us digging into their food. Mind you, it‚Äôs a small service of only 11-12 pax at the counter. How is it even possible to forget a customer‚Äôs order?

Corn ribs were surprisingly good albeit salty. Beef tartare was seasoned well but the pieces were roughly chopped. I had a few pieces which were too big. Presentation wise and from the diner‚Äôs perspective, the tartare can‚Äôt be seen. It‚Äôs hidden under the plain big piece of appalam. I would have preferred the appalam to be served at the side instead and not being advised to smash it with a spoon, where we ended up having uneven sized pieces to pair with the tartare. The famed bibimmyeon was pre-mixed, refrigerated and hand plated upon order. It had a bitter aftertaste and not the refreshing tangy spicy flavour profile you would have expected from a bibimmyeon. Prawn Pajeon though fried till crispy was more like a chive pajeon with prawn pieces placed atop. Sothi dipping sauce could be slightly more acidic to cut the greasiness of the fried pajeon. Pork rib though seasoned and grilled well was more American flavoured than Korean or Indian. No mention about water being charged by the bottle. The service staff was just overly enthusiastic in filling up our half-filled glasses with water and I only realised we were charged $10 for 2 bottles of water during payment when we didn‚Äôt even drink that much. Would have helped if the service staff could have kindly asked us if we needed more water and he can open another bottle of chargeable water for us.

I felt that the staff were just rushing through the service (get this over and done with attitude) and not sincere and passionate about in presenting a new form of fusion food. Seems like there is an invisible line between the cook staff and service/drink staff and I don‚Äôt feel a staff cohesion. Attention to detail in service was greatly lacking. A very disappointing experience.', 'date': 'a month ago', 'images': ['https://storage.googleapis.com/synthesis_geos_public/thumbnails/thumb_unavail.jpg']}, {'rating': 2, 'description': 'Understand that Korean and Indian cuisines both have strong flavours, but the seasoning in the food overall can be quite excessive. Especially the prawn maggi goreng and corn ribs. My tongue became a bit numb along the way and I started wishing the restaurant could have a more subtle and balanced flavour profile. The dessert (banana pie) was very pricey for its portion.', 'date': '2 weeks ago', 'images': ['https://storage.googleapis.com/synthesis_geos_public/thumbnails/thumb_unavail.jpg']}, {'rating': 2, 'description': "Difficult to square that it's backed by the same team as Thevar. Understand that the play is on a more casual take on Indian fusion but there was hardly any dish that really stood out (except maybe for the bibimmyeon). Some of the portions were pretty paltry for the price - the size of the murtabak just made me sad. The mains came almost 15 mins late and service was quite inattentive despite there being only 4-5 parties in the restaurant. Frankly expected a lot more given Thevar's reputation and their two Michelin stars. Hope they really turn it around - regardless of the experience I still think it's a promising concept.", 'date': 'a week ago', 'images': ['https://storage.googleapis.com/synthesis_geos_public/thumbnails/thumb_unavail.jpg']}, {'rating': 2, 'description': 'I FEEL CHEATED

TLDR; I will not come here again and I DO NOT RECOMMEND it to others. Save your money, go eat at a mamak instead.

When you're seated, they ask if you want still or sparkling water without telling you the they will charge you $5 FREAKING DOLLARS PER PERSON FOR A GLASS OF "FANCY" TAP WATER, even if you order other expensive drinks like cocktails or get a bottle of wine.

They also flout NEA rules because the restaurant is seated bar style with the kitchen right behind the counter but none of the BOH or FOH (who are also behind the counter) are wearing masks - this considering they've got their faces close to the dishes they plate while using tweezer tongs.

[{'rating': 5, 'description': 'First visit to this bar and definitely not the last! Love everything about this bar from the vibe to the food!

Located in the basement of the Forum shopping centre, this Japanese bar was cosy and crowded on a Saturday night. We had the brussel sprouts, oyako don, salmon aburi mentai maki and skewers. Absolutely love the food here especially their signature Brussel Sprouts. It was so good we were tempted to order a second serving.

Will definitely be back to try other cocktails and food on their menu!', 'date': 'a week ago', 'images': ['https://storage.googleapis.com/synthesis_geos_public/thumbnails/thumb_unavail.jpg']}, {'rating': 5, 'description': "This is my first time there and it was an impromptu dinner arrangement so I had no expectations at all.

We ordered from the grill menu and we tried the sparkling sake. The food was perfectly executed... the quail eggs, though grilled, still had a runny yolk and the charred and smokey flavour from the bincho came through in all the food we ordered.

We were recommended to try the chicken ramen, which is a signature dish. Apparently the broth is made from 40kg worth of French poulet chicken... which explains why it's so flavourful and full of collagen and umami.

Jack, the in-house sake sommelier was a very good host. For sake lovers... this is one of 3 restaurants in Singapore that serve draft sake and the only one that has a custom chiller so that the temperature of the sake is just right.

There's a wide variety of sake and the right menu to pair with the drinks. A very nice place to enjoy Japanese grill and sake.

Sit at the bar if you can and get to know the staff who make the food... they are a friendly bunch with interesting stories to share... if you are willing to listen.", 'date': '9 months ago', 'images': ['https://storage.googleapis.com/synthesis_geos_public/thumbnails/thumb_unavail.jpg']}, {'rating': 5, 'description': 'What a great experience we had at Nomi dining Bar.

review_sample:
[{'rating': 5, 'description': 'The food was really good and quite surprising. Everything was really original and tasty. Special mention for the main courses which were amazing, espacially the Mussels one. I was also quite surprised, in a good way, by the wines. The only thing I can say is that it was a little too cold in the room for me. Thank you very much for the experience.', 'date': '4 days ago', 'images': ['https://storage.googleapis.com/synthesis_geos_public/thumbnails/thumb_unavail.jpg']}, {'rating': 5, 'description': 'The dining experience was very enjoyable. I thought the overall ambience and plating / presentation were 10/10. What stood out most was the hospitality. The staff noted it was my husband‚Äôs birthday and gave a little something which was thoughtful and useful - a little goodie bag comprising samplers of Irish cream, the very same bacon butter that came with the soda bread in the menu, and a useful fridge magnet with the recipe of the said bread. Such a nice way to remember the meal by!', 'date': '3 months ago', 'images': ['https://storage.googleapis.com/synthesis_geos_public/thumbnails/thumb_unavail.jpg']}, {'rating': 5, 'description': 'Absolutely incredible culinary experience. Came here during restaurant week and had their lunch menu for $128++.

Looking at the names of the dishes, it wasn‚Äôt the typical fine dining I was used to. And I didn‚Äôt give much thought to it.

I arrived shortly after 12pm on a Friday. The venue wasn‚Äôt big, but spacious enough so as not to be too close to the other table. It was slightly dimmed with dark blue walls which gave a very cosy and unorthodox vibe. We were shown our menu and the staff promptly explained to us the concept behind the menu and the background of the name of the restaurant. Basically it is an Ireland inspired menu.

Each item was crafted with an inspiration and/or ingredient from Ireland. And each dish was perfect in terms of taste and execution. No one dish was something I‚Äôve had elsewhere, with ingredients carefully but smartly infused into each item. We were also given a foie gras cr√®me br√ªl√©e out of courtesy as the kitchen was busy preparing an elaborate dish for a guest and took longer than usual. Superb classy touch there. It‚Äôs also worth mentioning this cr√®me br√ªl√©e was really delicious, whereby I believe the foie gras was actually infused into the egg custard. Turned out to be the favorite dish of my companion.

If anything, the only slight let down were the dessert and the Brie cheese add on. The dessert was beautifully executed however in terms of presentation I would have preferred something more precise. The Brie cheese was closer to a blue cheese, and I felt we could have been warned as the typical Brie cheese would not taste like that.

Aside from that, I had a really good time and would recommend this place!', 'date': '5 months ago', 'images': ['https://storage.googleapis.com/synthesis_geos_public/thumbnails/thumb_unavail.jpg']}, {'rating': 5, 'description': 'Excellent and innovative creations from beginning to end.

We started with the Soda, Stout and Treacle Bread.  Oh what and experience it was as it came with butter that had bacon bits and black onion powder infused in it.  The bread, served nicely warm, looked like a muffin and had great texture.

The Tayto Cheese & Onion was a tad too small, so could not taste the potato, nor cheese nor onion.

The Lovage & Jameson Soft Serve Asparagus Morel was like a tiny ice cream cone, delightful and playful.  Morels were made into a Ragu mousse and hidden deep in the cone.

A family favorite was the Salmon, Juniper & Seaweed which had Japanese influence, as salmon was cured for 3 days, then wrapped with seaweed and covered with crusty bread crumbs deep fried.  This was really a winner and we could eat 10 each, if given a choice.

Queen Scallop, Cider, Horseradish was a refreshing dish with icy yuzu taste, like a palate cleanser.

The Porridge of Sea Urchin was lovely, with generous amount of sea urchin and barley porridge covered with a beef tartare, another crowd pleaser.

The 7 Tales of the Fox & Silver Duck was a good mains.  With duck in 4 renditions, foie gras custard and green apple, chewy ball, crispy tart and duck meat with mulberries.

[{'rating': 4, 'description': "This is our 2nd visit. We love the food and the fact that it's a non pretentious place. We've felt really comfortable on both our visits. For starters we had the escargot and bone marrow. It was really good. We ordered 2 rib-eye with bearnaise sauce and a ravioli for mains.

The only thing we were not really comfortable with was how close the table next to us was. Overall we had a lovely time.", 'date': '5 months ago', 'images': ['https://storage.googleapis.com/synthesis_geos_public/thumbnails/thumb_unavail.jpg']}, {'rating': 4, 'description': 'Stepping inside Brasserie Gavroche, it had a nice old rustic charm to it, with the vintage looking wooden furnitures and 50s style hanging lights. Not a typical fine dinning setting but more of a simple sit down dinning for a close group of friends to meet up and chat over a hearty meal.

The restaurant serves some of the more classical French dishes such as foil gras and escargot, with choices of either cold or warm appetisers dishes. It seems the white asparagus is in season now and we ordered 1/2 dozen of escargots and the foie gras (served with toasted country bread) to go with it for our starters.

The escargot was baked with parsley and garlic butter. Classical proven dish that couldn‚Äôt really go wrong, but nothing outstanding either. Felt that the escargots was a tad over baked for me as the meat was slightly tough. Overall the taste was rich and flavourful, and the leftover butter oil makes great dip for the bread. 3/5

The white asparagus was served with Parma ham, Benedict eggs and hollandaise sauce. The asparagus was crunchy and juicy, and would have paired perfectly with the savoury ham, if not for the lingering bitter vegetal aftertaste coming from the asparagus. Not sure what the Benedict egg and hollandaise sauce bring to the dish, didn‚Äôt think the sauce went well with the dish. 3/5

The foie gras serving was generous! Some of the inferior foie gras I tasted had a powdery and crumbly texture with a strong metallic iron aftertaste lingering. But the foie gras served here was of a much higher quality. Smooth and buttery with a right proportion of fat; lighter in taste but yet flavourful (from the meat) and rich without being too overpowering. It left you wanting to try more as it didn‚Äôt have the saturating greasy feeling. The yellow portion of the foie gras in the picture was actually solidified fat and simply pure decadent! I would strongly encourage everyone to at least try a small bit of it to savour the slow melting of pure animal fat essence in your mouth! The reddish condiment at the side was some sort of dried fruit puree and the slight sweet-sourness went very well with the savoury foie gras. The only disappointment I had with the dish was the hard country bread, but otherwise excellent dish. 4.5/5

We ordered 3 mains for sharing:  lamb tongue (not in regular menu), beef tartare and ribeye steak

Personally I prefer my lamb to be grilled for that rich ‚Äúmuttony‚Äù favour. This lamb tongue was stewed and served on top of potato mash. I chose this main as lamb tongue was an interesting cut I had not tried before despite the cooking style. The meat was tender with a bit of chewiness to it. Taste was delicately light and I hardly get any ‚Äòmuttony‚Äô favour in it. This was a very nice dish albeit it didn‚Äôt suit my personal taste preference. 3.5/5, only because of personal taste preference, otherwise the dish deserved a 4.

The beef tartare was disappointing. I loved the Angus beef for its ‚Äòsashimi freshness quality‚Äô with a slight chewy texture. But the condiment was a tad overpowering from the pungent shedded onion and the overly tangy dressing. I felt that the taste was off balanced in the mouth, skewing more towards the condiment. Texture was good, chewiness of the meat went well with the onion crunchiness. The bread was disappointing hard. 3/5

Saving the best for the last, the ribeye was the highlight of the meal for us. Perfectly grilled to medium rare with a pinkish tender center (an expected standard for any high end restaurant) and a slight crusty charred exterior. Decent fat content and the juice of the meat was well sealed during the cooking. Every mouthful was a fine balance of favour and texture. Tenderness of the meat interspersed with crispy charred parts, full bodied and juicy meat favour elevated by the light seasoning. It also went very well with the B√©arnaise sauce as it presented a different taste profile. Just to show you don‚Äôt need super expensive beef cut or A5 wagyu to enjoy a premium quality steak. 5/5', 'date': '5 months ago', 'images': ['https://storage.googleapis.com/synthesis_geos_public/thumbnails/thumb_unavail.jpg']}, {'rating': 4, 'description': 'Went for dinner
Ordered the onion soup, lamb rack and mussels
Had an amazing time wining and dining
The soup was delicious and fragrant
Lamb was very flavorful
Mussels was very fresh and tasty', 'date': '2 months ago', 'images': ['https://storage.googleapis.com/synthesis_geos_public/thumbnails/thumb_unavail.jpg']}, {'rating': 5, 'description': 'A Belgian in a French Brasserie‚Ä¶ what could possibly go wrong.

Nothing actually. Superb business lunch. Relaxing atmosphere, warm traditional interior, capable and attentive staff, and the food - oh man - the food!!

Tried the morel mushroom soup and the evergreen Angus Beef tartare. Sublime! Just the way I‚Äôd expect it in the best restaurant in Paris, or Brussels. And even the fries are ‚ÄúBelgian Approved‚Äù.

Thanks guys', 'date': '8 months ago', 'images': ['https://storage.googleapis.com/synthesis_geos_public/thumbnails/thumb_unavail.jpg']}, {'rating': 5, 'description': 'Lovely French-looking restaurant that‚Äôs well-lit too. [{'rating': 5, 'description': 'Fresh ingredient, complex texture and splendid tastes from individual dish. The complementary tomato is a highlight for my friend because the chef managed to "convince" her to eat tomato for the first time of her life. (my friend always threw away any signs of tomato from any dishes including omelets) Her comment was "this is the only way of cooking that can convince her to eat tomato in her life". [{'rating': 5, 'description': 'It‚Äôs so apt that this 1 Michelin starred restaurant is located within the Esplanade ‚Äî Singapore‚Äôs National performing art centre.

I now know why Labyrinth is #11 on the best Asian restaurant list for 2023, was awarded the highest climber award in 2023, and have 1 Michelin star.', 'date': '3 months ago', 'images': ['https://storage.googleapis.com/synthesis_geos_public/thumbnails/thumb_unavail.jpg']}, {'rating': 5, 'description': 'Wow, a great experience, one of the best meals I have had in my many years of travelling. The foie gras toast is definitely something you have to get when you're here. It melts quickly and pairs extremely well with the sweet jam and well toasted bread below. [{'rating': 5, 'description': 'Welcome Dinner for Managing Director 2 days ago at Golden Peony was pretty good! Waiters/Waitresses are very attentive to our wants and needs as and when needed.

Great service! Food was above average and environment is condusive for interaction between colleagues.

But Management would prefer to have private room for better communication between each other. But nevertheless, we enjoyed our dinner there :)', 'date': 'a week ago', 'images': ['https://storage.googleapis.com/synthesis_geos_public/thumbnails/thumb_unavail.jpg']}, {'rating': 5, 'description': "I went to a corporate dinner at Golden Peony, a Chinese restaurant, in a function room. They served each dish on its own plate, and the food was amazing. The sea perch was my favorite; it had a melt-in-your-mouth texture I'd never experienced before. The waitstaff was attentive, making the dining experience even better.", 'date': 'a month ago', 'images': ['https://storage.googleapis.com/synthesis_geos_public/thumbnails/thumb_unavail.jpg']}, {'rating': 4, 'description': 'The restaurant has a comfortable setting and the service is excellent.

The most memorable item from lunch was actually the tea. There is a fine selection of tea but the server was unable to tell some of the differences. Regardless, the tea was excellent.

The abalone was disappointing. The overpowering sea scent made the abalone taste stale. The other dishes were good, including the soup which was served hot.

The order in which the dishes are served can be better but overall, it was a good experience.', 'date': 'a month ago', 'images': ['https://storage.googleapis.com/synthesis_geos_public/thumbnails/thumb_unavail.jpg']}, {'rating': 5, 'description': "AWESOME PLACE TO HOLD A WEDDING :)

The best decision we ever made for our wedding was to host our wedding reception at Golden Peony! Although my husband and I don't live in Singapore, we wanted to celebrate with our family and friends here. The managers, Stanley and Vanessa, were incredibly understanding and responsive. I had some last-minute changes due to guest issues, and they did their best to accommodate them. For that, both my husband and I are truly thankful and grateful for their kindness and understanding.

The food was fantastic (I've attached photos for you to see); the taste and presentation exceeded our expectations. Initially, the food tasting didn't quite match our preferences, and we provided feedback. They worked diligently to perfect it to our taste buds. To this day, our guests still fondly remember the dishes they had and can't stop praising them.

The service from all the staff was exceptionally kind and helpful. They paid great attention to detail and ensured that our special day ran smoothly without any hiccups. From the tea ceremony to our grand entrance, champagne toasting, cake cutting, and serving dishes, everything went perfectly.

A heartfelt shoutout goes to the exceptional staff members who transformed our day into a truly beautiful and unforgettable experience. We extend our sincere gratitude to Stanley, Vanessa, Xiao Wei, Jane, Esther, XP, Wendy, and the numerous others whose contributions made our day so special. Your dedication to creating these cherished memories is deeply appreciated.

When we return to Singapore for a visit, there is no doubt that we will be returning to enjoy a casual meal at your restaurant. We wholeheartedly recommend it to others with 100% confidence!", 'date': 'a month ago', 'images': ['https://storage.googleapis.com/synthesis_geos_public/thumbnails/thumb_unavail.jpg']}, {'rating': 5, 'description': 'We dine here quite often - the most recent of which was during Restaurant Week where there was a fixed dinner menu. Unfortunately, on that evening, the kitchen stoves had issues and the chefs had to cook out of the hotel central kitchen. The wait was real but the staff were sincere and they extremely apologetic. Everyone at the restaurant were pretty calm about it as a result of the sincerity of the staff. Also, they gave a 15%/25% discount which was a welcome surprise to everyone which we only found out when we asked for the bill. Great service recovery.', 'date': '4 months ago', 'images': ['https://storage.googleapis.com/synthesis_geos_public/thumbnails/thumb_unavail.jpg']}, {'rating': 5, 'description': 'This chinese restaurant claims to serve sophisticated Cantonese cuisines and true enough, dishes that we ordered were truely delicious!

Crispy Egg Noodle with Half Lobster, consisted of Thick Egg Gravy (Well balanced in terms of flavour) with Ginger & Scallion, was great.

Sweet And Sour Pork with Mango‚Ä¶ Crispy on the outside and tender on the inside. Sauce was balanced and not too sweet, not overwhelming.

Mapo Beancurd with Plant Based Meat, Minced Mushrooms and Sze Chuan Peppercorn was a great Vegetarian dish.

For dessert, we settled for signature Chilled Cream Of Avocado with Basil Seed & Vanilla Ice Cream, and Chilled Mango Pudding with Sago & Pomelo. Both were good but not unforgetable.

Overall, as per website of restaurant, it does has an Elegant setting with Oriental influence, but sightly dimmer lighting should be more appropriate. Service staffs were attentive but need a bit more patient.', 'date': '3 months ago', 'images': ['https://storage.googleapis.com/synthesis_geos_public/thumbnails/thumb_unavail.jpg']}, {'rating': 5, 'description': "Nestled within the opulent confines of the Conrad hotel, The Golden Peony emerges as a beacon of Michelin-starred Chinese culinary artistry. Beyond its prestigious accolade, it's the restaurant's unwavering dedication to authentic Chinese flavors that truly sets it apart. On a recent visit, I was transported to the heart of China, with each dish narrating a tale of its rich culinary heritage. Their dim sum, a symphony of delicate flavors and textures, stands as a testament to their mastery. From the succulent har gow (shrimp dumplings) to the flavorful siu mai (pork and shrimp dumplings), each bite was a celebration of traditional craftsmanship. The staff's astute sensitivity to dietary preferences, crafting bespoke dishes for my companion, further elevated the dining experience. Their affability, combined with the surprisingly moderate tariffs for such a gourmet journey, is commendable. For those with an appreciation for the intricate nuances of Chinese cuisine and the art of dim sum, The Golden Peony is an experience not to be missed.", 'date': 'a month ago', 'images': ['https://storage.googleapis.com/synthesis_geos_public/thumbnails/thumb_unavail.jpg']}, {'rating': 5, 'description': 'Beautiful mooncake box with exquisite peony motifs! Received the Golden Peony Traditional Baked Treasures as a gift. Not sure how the mooncakes taste as I gave them away, but the packaging is absolutely a feast for the eyes!', 'date': '3 weeks ago', 'images': ['https://storage.googleapis.com/synthesis_geos_public/thumbnails/thumb_unavail.jpg']}]

The only criticism would be that the bread course was uninspiring, but who cares? It‚Äôs free anyway. Canap√©s started with their signature playful tomato soup. Using trompe l‚Äôoeil to make it look like tomatoes it‚Äôs actually a soft shell with tomato gazpacho encased within. The scallop tartare with avocado and tomato jelly was wonderfully light with all the elements working in harmony. The cod mousse taco was nice but overshadowed by its two counterparts. The first course started with a bang, yellowtail finished table side with a horseradish snow. Light, refreshing and full of flavour with an added air of theatricality for good measure. The second course was Mozambique langoustine which was the highlight of the menu. Sitting on top of a creamy anchovy sauce. The sweetness of the langoustine was a perfect complement to the (not-too) salty sauce. While the gem lettuce added some crunch to contrast with the soft and plump shellfish. This course was pure delight from start to finish! The pasta course was an elevated carbonara which utilised cured egg yolk. It was not too heavy which was a pleasant surprise. The main was veal with white asparagus coated in sabayon in a moscato sauce. The veal was cooked to perfection and the kitchen, once again, demonstrate their attention to detail by ensuring that each dish consists of an equal balance of flavours and textures. The palate cleanser was finished table side with a prickly pear granita, highly refreshing after two somewhat heavier courses. The dessert was the chef‚Äôs take on semifreddo using Marsala grapes, dessert wine sauce and clotted cream. Wonderful and I loved the bitterness of the grapes and wine sauce. Overall a spectacular meal, one of the best michelin-starred lunches one can grab in Singapore that showcases high quality ingredients, inventiveness while also not ripping a gigantic hole in one‚Äôs pocket. The good review first. Our appointment was at 7 however we were stuck in very bad traffic and we called to ask what‚Äôs the latest we could arrive. Location is beautiful and that kind of stirred our excitement for dinner as we‚Äôve had many magical Omakase experiences for lesser and we walked in with high hopes. It was my friend‚Äôs birthday and when the wait staff served the birthday dessert, she brought it in and left in on the table and walked off. No HBD greeting and no song. Wow. The lady at the payment  counter was just as disappointing. She did not ask us how we liked our dinner as she probably could sense our disappointment and yet did not bother to find out how they could have done better.
I truly believe that stellar service can turn around a mediocre dining experience, however a Michelin standard in food is just lost in bad service. Would go again !', 'date': '4 months ago', 'images': ['https://storage.googleapis.com/synthesis_geos_public/thumbnails/thumb_unavail.jpg']}, {'rating': 3, 'description': 'Was a consistent 5 and now a 3 and can easily get back to 5

Have been a big fan of Lantern for more than 10 years plus

The recent visit post Covid was frankly disappointing.

The views remain. spectacular, the music outstanding , signatures cocktails as good .

So WHY the 3 ?

Found that the serving crew and most of the bar staff relatively new and still trying to figure their way around. Part of our order was fairly simple. A neat single malt and a glass of Ros√©. The bar manager took our order and fulfilment was by a different person . The single malt arrived with ice and water and the glass of Ros√© wine never turned up. Had to remind the same bar manager abd finally it surfaced

Our classic fries order , we were being served someone else‚Äôs sweet potatoes fries, which were on the same tray. Had to correct the server and extract our fries.

Then for the first time saw a promotion offer on a trolley at Lantern. In my personal view such offers are best avoided in top ended bars as the person comes in and disturbs the flow of a conversation going on . However that was not the problem. The issue was you need to buy two glasses at the same time so then you end up with the second glass which would eventually be warm by the time you end up drinking the same. The bar manager again refused to serve the wines one after the other and insisted that both glasses of wine be placed at the same time

These are minor glitches and can easily be corrected by proper staffing and training to get the 3 to a 4.

Luckily for me spotted two familiar faces, Mr Haizul and Anna, who thanks to their intervention brought the situation to control.

Getting to 4 to 5 is simpler. Just by doing two things .

1. Please DO NOT STOP the music for 30 minutes, if the adjacent corporate event is having speeches going on. Not fair to the other paying guests. Solution is pretty simple just allow a 10 minute speech .

2. Also the Food menu requires a major makeover .

Getting from a 5 to 6 would be to get a NEA cigar smoking licence for the open area at the side of the pool. üòÄüòÄ

Finally, these are ALL minor irritants. Easily fixable and I look forward to soon going back and hopefully that time it will again be a 5 out of 5 experience', 'date': '3 months ago', 'images': ['https://storage.googleapis.com/synthesis_geos_public/thumbnails/thumb_unavail.jpg']}]

[{'rating': 5, 'description': "Good old Morton's.  It was the place to be back when I had an expense account, and my friends had a cigar locker.  I recently revisited, sans the expense account, so we sat at the bar and sampled from the appetizers menu. This did not save us a lot of money in the end, but it was a fun experience.  Not too many people sit in the actual bar inside the restaurant; they usually frequent the larger bar area on the level just above.  But we were old school and knew where to sit.  We got lots of attention from the friendly bartender and suggestions on drinks and food.  I have to say it was all good, but the highlight was the homemade potato chips with blue cheese dip.  Another highlight was the house-made ice cubes which are a very nice touch when spending a fortune on a cocktail.  It's rare that I give a restaurant 5 stars across the board for food/service/atmosphere, but this is an exception.  It's a chain, but still a must visit if you need a steak while in Singapore.", 'date': '3 weeks ago', 'images': ['https://storage.googleapis.com/synthesis_geos_public/thumbnails/thumb_unavail.jpg']}, {'rating': 5, 'description': '[Sep 2023] Newly renovated Morton‚Äôs brings a modern posh vibe with its contemporary interior. [{'rating': 4, 'description': 'Visited the restaurant for dinner and noticed that the ambiance was a bit too dim for my liking even though I like the vibes and art walls. Personally prefer slightly brighter for a more comfortable dining experience. The music was quite loud, making it difficult to have a conversation during dinner. Perhaps they could adjust the volume to create a more relaxed atmosphere, as the music might be more suitable for drinks and bar food instead of a proper dinner setting.

On the positive side, I found the cocktails menu interesting, and the food was quite good, especially the Tokyo hummus. Also, I was pleasantly surprised when they offered a complimentary piece of cake for a birthday celebration during our visit. This thoughtful gesture was greatly appreciated.

One thing to note that they charged $3 per person for the tap water. Surprised to see that in the bill', 'date': 'a month ago', 'images': ['https://storage.googleapis.com/synthesis_geos_public/thumbnails/thumb_unavail.jpg']}, {'rating': 4, 'description': 'Perfect place for drinks and chats, but wished the table and chair setting are more comfortable in style. Drinks menu is amazing with the fun touch of comic strips, too much ice for some and small amounts for indulgence. We ended with 3-4 glasses, adds swiftly onto check. Hummus with chips must-try as it‚Äôs a very different recipe from the usual. Wagyu gyozas and grilled eggplant are good too. Interestingly some dishes are in dainty fine-dine plating while some are casual bar snacks.', 'date': '3 months ago', 'images': ['https://storage.googleapis.com/synthesis_geos_public/thumbnails/thumb_unavail.jpg']}, {'rating': 5, 'description': 'Unassuming from the outside...but delivers on the inside. Might be a little loud for a big group. Loved the drink menu like a comic book with full proof, half proof and no proof drinks. I got the duck gyoza with foie gras and Chilean sea bass with truffle, ponzu and miso and both were awesome. Would definitely go back!', 'date': '2 months ago', 'images': ['https://storage.googleapis.com/synthesis_geos_public/thumbnails/thumb_unavail.jpg']}, {'rating': 4, 'description': 'The last time I visited Neon, it was more than a year ago, and I remembered being disappointed at the quality and pricing of the food.

This time, I was pleasantly surprised because it does feel like they have found the rhythm back in their stride. The food was lovely, and the cocktails, even classic ones that we ordered, were on point.

The tapas generally were very well balanced in terms of taste. The outstanding dish of the night was the amaebi served with wasabi tobiko on top of a crispy piece of chicken skin. The combination was sublime, with the freshness and sweetness of the shrimp complimenting that oily satisfying note from the chix skin.

The hamachi sashimi was fresh, served over ponzu. The bone marrow with uni was done really well, served with decadent brioche, and just the right amount of savory and sweetness. I usually worry if the uni is fresh but the uni quality was exceptional.

The duck foie gras dumplings were yunmy, only complaint is that I can‚Äôt really taste the foie, but still a satisfying dish.

The chilean seabass was perfectly cooked with bits of crispy garlic, and overall a perfect ending to the meal.

They make a really mean campari sour, and their old fashioneds weren‚Äôt shabby as well.

Overall fun environment to be in, will be back.', 'date': 'a month ago', 'images': ['https://storage.googleapis.com/synthesis_geos_public/thumbnails/thumb_unavail.jpg']}, {'rating': 5, 'description': 'Went for the special taco brunch with guest chef from Hong Kong‚Ä¶I must say‚Ä¶BEST TACO‚Äôs I‚Äôve had in Singapore hands down! I know this was the guest chef and we haven‚Äôt been for a regular meal here so not sure if the regular menu is just as tasty or not but man‚Ä¶amazing! The biggest complaint is the price, $22 for 1 or 2 taco‚Äôs depending and $25/ea drink adds up quickly. We were lucky that the food was amazing or because it cost a pretty penny.  I‚Äôve seen several other events that Neon Pigeon has hosted but haven‚Äôt been able to join before this one. It‚Äôs great that they have these events and change things up from time to time.

Overall the place is super cool and hip! I love the vibe they have going and I have been trying to make it to here for some time so I‚Äôm happy that we went. The service was a bit slow and you have to flag down the waiters which was annoying. The food came out really slow at first but I must say the manager owned up to it and came to share his apologies for the delay which was really really nice. Because of this I am sure this is a good place to visit again and I‚Äôm looking forward to going back.', 'date': '5 months ago', 'images': ['https://storage.googleapis.com/synthesis_geos_public/thumbnails/thumb_unavail.jpg']}, {'rating': 5, 'description': 'Went for a birthday celebration. The food was exceptionally great. We ordered the Tokyo Hummus which we enjoyed very much. It was an upgraded version of your normal hummus. The next dish that blew my mind was the Caramelized Brussels Sprouts. It was so amazing we ordered a second portion of it. The duck gyoza was alright.

The bo-ssam was tender and juicy. The marinate on it was great. The grilled salmon was nicely cooked and has that melt in your mouth feeling.

The truffle mushroom rice was my other favourite.

The sashimi from Moriawase was very fresh but the quantity could be more.

The drinks there were very unique.

I would say I had a very good experience at Neon Pigeon. The food was amazing.  The staff was even better.

Although I hope that the lights can be turned on a
Little brighter.

The price is on the higher side but I guess you pay for the quality and service.

[{'rating': 5, 'description': 'From the moment you step foot onto their premise, along the hallway to your intended dining place, the greeting from staff in uniform  were warm & friendly.

[{'rating': 5, 'description': 'I absolutely loved the food, especially the beef and scallops! The Chinese 8-course meal left me completely satisfied, and the service was excellent. The vinyl provides a nice ambience. Cocktails were really tasty and you‚Äôre paying for that premium service at 30$ a drink. Feels like a place you might go for a business meeting over drinks.', 'date': '4 months ago', 'images': ['https://storage.googleapis.com/synthesis_geos_public/thumbnails/thumb_unavail.jpg']}, {'rating': 4, 'description': "Beautiful bar with an amazing concept. RPM has hundreds of Vinyl LPs and a great sound system including old-school turntables. I wish they'd let you request certain albums but understand how that could be messy. Beautiful homey wood furniture and decor with warm lighting and a comfy bar counter. If I opened a bar, I'd want it to look like RPM. Service is also knowledgeable and happy to share as much about shochu as they can.

I'm a big shochu fan and to see a whole bar dedicated to shochu warms my heart. Sadly though, the prices are just a bit too crazy! Shochu should be pretty cheap, which is one of its great attractions, but they start shochu by the glass at 25 SGD! Even for stuff like Mitake or Rento (which probably cost SGD 20 for a bottle at retail!). A glass of Maoh (which admittedly is hard to find) goes for SGD 60! Totally crazy. Cocktails are 27 SGD each, which is reasonable I suppose.

In terms of cocktails, they try to use shochu as the base ingredient in most of them, and they more or less work. The martini & gimlet I had were good, though a bit light, since shochu is usually just 25% APV, while the Tea/Rice Shochu was a bit bitter.

In all, I believe shochu should be for everyone, made for the masses, though of course, there are premium brands and makers. However, the prices at RPM, even for the everyday convenience store shochus, are excluding a lot of the potential market. Wish they lowered shochu by-the-glass prices to reflect their actual cost, while they can continue to mark up cocktails and rarer shochus", 'date': '3 months ago', 'images': ['https://storage.googleapis.com/synthesis_geos_public/thumbnails/thumb_unavail.jpg']}, {'rating': 4, 'description': 'Nice cocktail bar, highball was great. The female snow crab dish was the worst because you had to assemble it onto your spoon yourself so it‚Äôs constant trial and error without the ability to achieve the optimum flavour of the dish - snow crab is meant to be sweet and delicious but this dish was a complete disappointment.', 'date': '10 months ago', 'images': ['https://storage.googleapis.com/synthesis_geos_public/thumbnails/thumb_unavail.jpg']}, {'rating': 5, 'description': 'Highly recommend this lovely place for Japanese food that are prepared straight from the heart. I had the Ninja lunch set which I delightfully enjoyed every course of the meal. Chef Asai and his team delivers wonderful high quality food that are so good and will probably make anyone‚Äôs day! I will definitely be back again with my friends! üëçüèª', 'date': '11 months ago', 'images': ['https://storage.googleapis.com/synthesis_geos_public/thumbnails/thumb_unavail.jpg']}, {'rating': 2, 'description': 'Disappointing experience for Yakatori fans.

I love Yakatori, it‚Äôs a twice a month treat. So when Bincho opened up again with Cloudstreet backing, we had to go.

Whilst they serve a decent range of chicken cuts and grill the meat over charcoal Bincho do not skewer the meat.

Does that matter? Yes. Very much.
A skewer is is constructed to give a specific surface area, meat to fat ratio and cleaned up to look enticing. But most of all, it‚Äôs an eating experience. Each stick prepared and served to you, bite sized and seasoned at the peak of its perfection.

Serving whole pieces reduces the whole experience. Bincho also serve seasonings (flavoured salts) next to almost every dish. For me this removes the chefs experience and skill and you run the risk of over seasoned bites with an over ambitious dip‚Ä¶

More issues with Bincho style:
1. They slice the big cuts too thin, this ruins the textual difference you look for in Yakatori.
2. They cook skin to chewy rather than crispy, this extenuates the fatty feeling.
3. They rest the meat - normally a great thing as it makes it juicer. But for me it means the pieces come out cool and missing that exciting freshness you get from a stick freshly picked off the grill.

Now let‚Äôs talk price. The chicken cuts are priced reasonably ($8-24) as you get whole pieces or multiple items per plate.

But look across at the side dishes and plates you get an all together different feeling. We got one small salad (literally 2 baby courgette - smaller than my finger) and half a dozen leaves for $32! That‚Äôs unjustifiable.  Prices for single plates currently go up to $160!!! So you‚Äôd better bring a rich friend if you want to eat a balanced meal or try something a little different.

PS: The ‚Äòcrispy rice ball‚Äô - The smallest rice ball I‚Äôve ever seen for $20 - you should also know, it‚Äôs covered in salmon, row and bottarga - maybe you see that as good value‚Ä¶ but it‚Äôs not what we expected, served with a thimble (half) full of soup.

If you‚Äôve read this far congratulations! Let me reward you with 2 great Yakatori suggestions in Singapore:

Shirokane Tori-Tama  - enjoy a massive range of cuts cooked to perfection.

Yakitori Yatagarasu - sit at the bar and buy the staff a drink for a great night of classic Yakatori.', 'date': 'a year ago', 'images': ['https://storage.googleapis.com/synthesis_geos_public/thumbnails/thumb_unavail.jpg']}, {'rating': 5, 'description': "Google needs to provide the option to give more than 5 stars for places that exceed your expectations. Because Bincho is definitely one of them... every single dish was of high quality and tasted like something I've never had before.. Service was amazing as well!! Their grilled cabbage salad really took me by surprise. Who would've though cabbage could taste this good!", 'date': 'a year ago', 'images': ['https://storage.googleapis.com/synthesis_geos_public/thumbnails/thumb_unavail.jpg']}]

[{'rating': 5, 'description': "Nice ambience, great service and tasty food. It may be a bit on the high side for the price, but with that kind of service quality and food, worth to pay the price.

Brought my mum to celebrate Mother's Day today and am so happy that she enjoyed a lot. My mum has a very high standard of requirement for food, not many restaurants met her standard, but this restaurant make it!

Highly recommended.", 'date': 'a year ago', 'images': ['https://storage.googleapis.com/synthesis_geos_public/thumbnails/thumb_unavail.jpg']}, {'rating': 3, 'description': 'This was a difficult review/rating - although the service was excellent, the dishes were 50% hits; 50% misses‚Ä¶ in the end, I settled at 3stars from a price to value perspective.

Service 1st (which I know a lot of people pay for, incl myself, for going to imperial treasure) - well paced dining experience! Front service captain was not pushy in dishes and made appropriate suggestions to prevent over-ordering. Pace of dishes were relaxed and well timed.

Hits - The roe crab was top notched, hangs in there amongst the best teochew restaurants in SG. Funny that I had the Christian (flower) crabs here before and I tot the cheaper roe crab is way better (~50% cheaper). Perhaps I just like roe, but that said, the roe crab flesh here is nicely & subtly sweet. We also had a soon-hock steamed teochew style - super fresh super juicy and all the soup perfect for making a Ê±§È•≠!

Misses - the braised stuffs were really disappointing - duck meat, liver & gizzard. The meat was ok but you can get this everywhere incl. your favourite hawker, the liver was off for me, it had that offal taste which I hope had been better processed. The gizzard is the rubbery crunchy style which I didn‚Äôt like. The oyster omelete was also a let-down after having tried so many teochew restaurants in SG. The style here is really the hawker Center style with a better finish in appearance - slightly crisp on the outsides with soft gooey center. Oysters quantity n quality were not especially memorable.

Others - some other dishes that were unremarkable (well made but not surprisingly good nor bad) were their kai-lan horfun & kai-lan with sole fish.', 'date': 'a year ago', 'images': ['https://storage.googleapis.com/synthesis_geos_public/thumbnails/thumb_unavail.jpg']}, {'rating': 4, 'description': 'They have 2 floors of the restaurant. Private rooms at level 2 and restaurant setting at level 3. Ambience is not too bad but I do feel abit tight space at the restaurant setting.

The staff was apologetic and offered to change a new cup for me. We paid $336 in total for 4 persons.', 'date': '2 years ago', 'images': ['https://storage.googleapis.com/synthesis_geos_public/thumbnails/thumb_unavail.jpg']}, {'rating': 4, 'description': "This visit was made back in late-November 2021.

Empress Dowager wanted to try another Teochew Cuisine place and selected Imperial Treasure Fine Teochew Cuisine at Guoco Tower to sample.

Arrived at the restaurant and we were shown a booth space. Unfortunately, such booth space can only fit people who are slim. All 8 of their 2-person booth tables were empty as even a slim pregnant lady with her husband were seated at at 5 person table given that the booths could not fit her pregnant belly either. Definitely a disaster in terms of the person who decided to install such small booths.

The lady at the front initially asked us to wait but after 5 minutes, asked the VIP section at Level 2 to take us in instead. Level 3 is where the general crowd heads to, while Level 2 are the VIP Rooms where a minimum spend is required if asking for such rooms.

The food here is mostly acceptable. Unfortunately, a key Teochew dish of Chilled Crab with Roe is currently unavailable as the restaurant claims their supplier does not have stock at the moment. Another pity is that their Teochew Style Plain Porridge lacked the accompanying condiments as only the plain porridge was served. Other than that, there were some other hits. Especially loved the Wok-Fried Hor Fun with Diced Kailan & Preserved Radish, as it had excellent Wok Hei and was really tasty.

General Verdict: Teochew Cuisine in fine dining style that is good for a visit. Poor design of table booths that shows no consideration was given to humans actual size but consideration was given to putting in more tables only. Will need to work harder to live up to the 1 Michelin Star at its sister restaurant at Ion Orchard

Also their mushroom + abalone soup is also a good one, its presentation is also stunning as the soup itself.

What make me to leave a 2star review are their instability in delivering high quality, and their response to it.

One of their dishes is fresh oyster served with eel. It may be very dependent on people taste, but I found my oysters were not fresh at all. It could be an one off case, as later i found my girlfriend‚Äôs one is tasting fine.

However, the worst part is all the eel fish on my plate have fish bone in it, and one even stuck out of the meat. This eel isn‚Äôt served as one big piece or as one whole fish, which both are common to have a few bones in it. This is served as a delicate and finely-cut cube, which I believe everyone would expect there shouldnt be bones in it, let alone sticking out.

I was disappointed at the time, and reported that to their waiter in a peaceful manner. I had no intention to fuss around at then as it could just be a careless mistake.

But the response I got is outrageous. I was told because it‚Äôs an eel, bone is expected to be in it. So, my understanding from them is why should I complain about it as fish always has bones. It might sounds fair, but as said it is a delicate and finely cut cube where removing bone should be part of the process and chef should make every possible effort to make sure of it. I cannot accept it is not seen as an oversight and i‚Äôm even more disappointed the chef and waiter thought it is ok.

The other dish (the so-called signature scallop), as a Michelin star restaurant, how can you not clean the plate before serving, leaving some oil drops splashing around it. It totally affected my dining experience.

throughout the evening, i have also witnessed waiter reminded their chef they have ingredients missed to include in their dishes. If your restaurant is serving in an open kitchen style, this is basically a disaster to see.

The restaurant has prided themselves to be continuously Michelin starred. If this is the standard Michelin wants to demonstrate, I am deeply concerned.', 'date': 'a year ago', 'images': ['https://storage.googleapis.com/synthesis_geos_public/thumbnails/thumb_unavail.jpg']}, {'rating': 5, 'description': 'Had a wonderful lunch at Beni. [{'rating': 4, 'description': 'Tried their popular Dry Dan Dan Noodles, which spice level is customisable, and I got the Medium one. review_sample:
[{'rating': 5, 'description': 'TOP notch Italian food, prices are also on the higher side (pasta $40-50, beef $70-100+). In return you get quality for what you pay for. Definitely not a daily dining Italian shop. I came with my friend for a celebration.

Shop opens up with a bar, and then leads you into a dining area where there were ample space and ambience was on point. Good vibes.

Warm bread was fluffy and tasted perfect when dipped with a their top grade olive oil and a touch of balsamic vinegar. Starter was ok. Mushroom soup done right, service was prompt, pastas were all round tasty (one of the best), beef steak was done exactly the way I wanted it, not over cooked and not under cooked, tiramisu was a good old recipe that is worth it.

I must also comment that the restaurant made an effort to portion the food for 2 for every ordered item, when they noted we were sharing everything, this I‚Äôm very appreciative of.

The only thing I thought could be better were the bread sticks offered on the table, they were lacklustre as a tidbit or small bite. Maybe it‚Äôs just me but I saw most tables did not bother to eat or touch.

Overall, this restaurant definitely deserves a 5 stars.', 'date': 'a week ago', 'images': ['https://storage.googleapis.com/synthesis_geos_public/thumbnails/thumb_unavail.jpg']}, {'rating': 4, 'description': 'We were here for SG restaurant week and had the set lunch menu.

review_sample:
[{'rating': 5, 'description': 'This place has a wow factor. The 19th floor view of Marina Bay Sands and its surroundings are astounding. Service was impeccable.

The angel hair pasta was one of the best I ever tasted. The halibut was perfectly done. I don't like fish that is overcooked. The duck breast did not have any gamely taste. The "melt in the mouth" beef cheek was tender and tasty. Definitely worth a second visit.', 'date': 'a month ago', 'images': ['https://storage.googleapis.com/synthesis_geos_public/thumbnails/thumb_unavail.jpg']}, {'rating': 5, 'description': 'My second visit. My last visit was during the pandemic.

Today‚Äôs lunch was very satisfactory. Food was improved than last time. It is not amazing but good. They allowed us to choose 2 appetisers for 3 course meal, which was satisfying.

Service was flawless.
Atmosphere is great- it is quiet so you can actually hear what your friends are saying (in many restaurants in Singapore, it can get quite rowdy and you cannot hear what those sitting next to you say)‚Ä¶here they provide ample space and long distance between tables. Ceiling is high and the whole space is quite magnificent.

All of my friends felt it was not bad value for money. We usually dine in hotels and fine restaurants. So my standards might be a little bit different from tourists.

We love the view. I have been to many places with the MBS view (Jaan, Smoke & Mirrors, Art, Dolce Vita, Level 33, One Fullerton area, Monti, Fullerton Bay hotel, Fullerton Hotel and so on)‚Ä¶ but I think this place has the best view.

The only downside is they open new bottles of water without informing us. We thought we had two bottles but we ended up paying for three bottles of sparkling water. review_sample:

[{'rating': 2, 'description': 'It may not be fair to judge a restaurant by ordering dim sum dishes knowing that‚Äôs not what they are known for. [{'rating': 4, 'description': "Food was really good for its price. We had the Colorful Cloud Dinner Set Menu. I will say it started out amazing and plateaued off around the main course. But for its price I am won't be too picky. Service was good, staffs were friendly and professional. The revolving platform gave a 360 view of the city which was a huge plus for me. Will recommend!", 'date': 'a month ago', 'images': ['https://storage.googleapis.com/synthesis_geos_public/thumbnails/thumb_unavail.jpg']}, {'rating': 5, 'description': "I had the pleasure of indulging in an exquisite dining experience at T√≥ng L√® Private Dining, and I can confidently say it was an absolute delight for all the senses. The first thing that captivated me upon entering here was the stunning view. The restaurant's unique concept of a rotating dining room allowed me to indulge in a 360-degree panorama of the cityscape, adding a sense of wonder and spectacle to the already exquisite dining affair. The menu was a testament to the chef's creativity and culinary expertise. Each dish was a harmonious blend of flavours, beautifully presented and bursting with vibrant colours and textures. I must also mention the impeccable timing of the service. Each course was served with precision, allowing us to savor every bite without feeling rushed. The staff's attention to detail and their commitment to providing exceptional service truly enhanced the entire dining affair. Overall, my dining experience at here was an unforgettable journey of culinary delight and I cannot wait to return to experience their wonders once again :)", 'date': '3 months ago', 'images': ['https://storage.googleapis.com/synthesis_geos_public/thumbnails/thumb_unavail.jpg']}, {'rating': 5, 'description': "Quality of food matches the price. The family all agreed it was a perfect place for a family celebration. The service was immaculate and staff very attentive to details. We didn't mention it was a BD celebration but when we clinked our wine glasses, they must have overheard us saying Happy BD, and they surprised us with longevity buns. They also understand Chinese etiquette well as our son discreetly wanted to foot the bill, but the attending staff came quietly to check with my husband who was the host if they should accept my son's card. That's so thoughtful as in Chinese custom the host foots the bill and they respected that.", 'date': 'a week ago', 'images': ['https://storage.googleapis.com/synthesis_geos_public/thumbnails/thumb_unavail.jpg']}, {'rating': 5, 'description': 'Most rotating restaurants live off the gimmick of being exactly that - a rotating restaurant offering a 360 degree view of a location. Many times, the food in such restaurants isn‚Äôt a priority, but the experience is. This restaurant, however, serves excellent food and offers a great view of Marina Bay Sands and the fountain and light show in front of the mall, as well as a nice view of parts of the Singapore skyline. The rotation is very slow and it take about two hours to do a full 360 revolution. If you are unlucky, you will be at the opposite side of the fountain show both times it occurs. For a period of the 360 tour you are very close to an office building - so close that you can see the monitors of the people working in the building.

The seating arrangement is varied, from two/four person tables, to separate dining rooms for larger groups. The restaurant has a very good bar which has a great selection of cocktails and spirits. The restaurant is quiet which makes it easy to have a business conversation, if that‚Äòs why you are there.

The restaurant offers a seven-course menu which is perfectly timed for a two-hour dining experience. The wine menu is very extensive and there is a sommelier that can provide advice if you require so. The menu was extremely well thought-through and the various dishes were perfectly combined to provide a first-class dining experience.

The staff is very attentive and friendly, and made us feel welcome from the minute we set foot in the restaurant.

We would come to this restaurant again, and in particular for the dining experience. We were positively surprised by every course.

Made a booking due to good review + menu and food offerings to our liking. Took up the newly launched Omakase menu (thanks for the discount!) and paid slightly over 200 Inc taxes.

We had an enjoyable dining experience at this modern Izakaya with Chef Kan presenting each course in front of us and explaining each dish - running seasonal ingredients of summer imported from Japan.

We loved all the dishes, thoroughly enjoyed the dining experience, and wrapped up the night with a refreshing sorbet.

Worth to give Ippai a try. And we will return for a-la-carte menu as we have so much food yet to try out.

Personally, I think the waitress can be more attentive.', 'date': '4 months ago', 'images': ['https://storage.googleapis.com/synthesis_geos_public/thumbnails/thumb_unavail.jpg']}, {'rating': 3, 'description': 'There is complimentary parking space outside of the restaurant, subject to availability.

Decor is snazzy and spacious.

Was impressed by the prompt text directly sent by restaurant after my reservation on Chope to clarify my queries. Used the entertainer app for mains upon arrival.

They do have attractive 1-for-1 offerings for hot sides and happy hour. Special promotions on Mondays for beer and Wednesdays for ladies.

We were divided over which is the better main for the hotate spag and wagyu fried rice. The ehire is average.

Had our bill sorted out 3 times due to additional item from another table and wrong lower priced item keyed in revision. Do check yours.', 'date': '4 months ago', 'images': ['https://storage.googleapis.com/synthesis_geos_public/thumbnails/thumb_unavail.jpg']}, {'rating': 4, 'description': "I actually noticed Ippai from quite a long time ago since the eclectic exterior design of neon lights, Japanese ukiyo-e drawings is very striking. But since it is located within Dorsett Hotel, I had assumed it is a Japanese Buffet. Yes. I should have known it‚Äôs lzakaya instead due to the setting. Anyway, better late than never.

I‚Äôm all hyped up to try the food here the moment I saw its menu featuring Japanese Tapas, called Tapasu in Japanese Romanji. I like unique concept of Japanese food served in small plates so that I can try more menu items in one sitting. In addition, the food here is pretty unique, and of course yummy, so dining here is a worthwhile experience.

The interior of Ippai is that of modern, cool, upmarket Izakaya style. A great place to chill, get comfy, enjoy some good food with friends. And enjoy some sake while at it lol

The service is also very good and attentive. And they make some good recommendations on sake and food. In addition, it‚Äôs nice that they let me know of this ‚Äúone for one tapas‚Äù promotion so as to be kinder to my wallet üëçüèª

The very interesting Negitoro Cone is packed with so many ingredients, as evident from the photo, and so much flavours. Creaminess, umami, tangy zest, planty pungency all stuffing into the cute cones, whose crunchiness works very well to enhance the overall texture. I also love the thoughtfulness for wrapping the cones with paper.

Kurobuta Miso Yaki is pretty juicy with nice lightly charred exterior, and comes miso sauce and mayonnaise. A hearty nice treat to munch on.

I love Ebi Tartar Yaki. This is my favourite of the night. Lightly seasoned with a dollop of tartar and a dose ofvflying fish roe, the subtle briny sweetness of the succulent prawns shines through and takes the centrestage.

Hotate Truffle Uni Ice-cream is so luxurious. The uni ice-cream at the centre is naturally sweet with a lace of umami. It‚Äôs coldness complements the scallop slices very well. It‚Äôs decadent and delicious, but the price is much steeper than that of other dishes.

There is interesting trio of sake pairing, and it's for twenty bucks only. Super value for money.

Besides the items I had tried, here are lots of other unique dishes in the menu. I want to try them too!

By the way, this restaurant serves Don sets instead during lunch. Some look interesting, but since I‚Äôm more for the experience, I opted for dinner to try the tapas.

Thoughts: Nice Unique Japanese Tapas", 'date': '4 months ago', 'images': ['https://storage.googleapis.com/synthesis_geos_public/thumbnails/thumb_unavail.jpg']}]

[{'rating': 5, 'description': "I recently had the pleasure of indulging in Rubato's lunch buffet, and it was truly a memorable experience. The restaurant provided impeccable service, and the buffet itself offered a delightful selection of Italian dishes.

From the moment I walked in, the staff at Rubato made me feel welcome and ensured that I had everything I needed throughout the meal. Their attention to detail and dedication to guest satisfaction were evident.

The lunch buffet at Rubato featured a wide variety of Italian classics, from fresh salads and antipasti to hearty pasta dishes and delectable desserts. The flavors were outstanding, and the buffet's diverse offerings catered to a range of tastes. It's a fantastic option for those looking to explore a variety of Italian flavors in one sitting.

The only area where Rubato could improve was in the presentation of the main courses on the buffet. The plating of the meats and sauces at the start could be refined to make it easier for diners to identify and enjoy each dish.

In summary, Rubato's lunch buffet offers an exceptional culinary journey through Italian cuisine, with outstanding service to match. [{'rating': 5, 'description': 'My wife and I visited the restaurant last night (15 Oct 2023). The food is good, ambience is nice and the services are prompt.

We ordered two Antipasti which was great, came serving hot. The complementing sweat from the asparagus and savory pharma ham mix well. Mixed grilled vegetables was a great mix of tastes too with zucchini, olive, capsicum, etc.

Mains came serving hot, both mains are great, creamy with complementing textures from the mushrooms for risotto (Risotto con Funghi Porcini) and sausages for the pasta (Fettuccine alla Nocerina).
What I like best about the dessert is the lemon cake (Torta al Limone) served warm which is a plus. Tiramisu is fantastic that does not require any further introductions.

Food wise, we tried a mix of the small plates (padron peppers, mushrooms with chorizo, clams) and they were alright, but nothing to shout about. Overall, we left the dinner still pretty hungry and not very satisfied with the meal and ended up going next door for another round of dinner. [{'rating': 5, 'description': 'The view is amazing! The staff is pretty considerate, even I didn‚Äôt manage to book outdoor table online, they give me one when it‚Äôs available on spot. For desserts, we ordered the banoffee tart, mango & coconut parfait which looked very refined & tasted yummy while the beer ice/cream was a bit underwhelming, texture was coarse, beer note was not prominent. I must say the service here is top notch with special mention to Calvin who attended to us. He was very friendly & patient in explaining the menu.  It is highly recommended for celebration of special occasions with good view & good food combination. Didn‚Äôt try the food but love the atmosphere and kind staff', 'date': 'a week ago', 'images': ['https://storage.googleapis.com/synthesis_geos_public/thumbnails/thumb_unavail.jpg']}, {'rating': 3, 'description': "Tucked at the 2nd floor, HKK is a speakeasy by Zouk Group, located away from the buzz and bustle of Clarke Quay.

Huevos Estrellados is a dish involving eggs fried in a large amount of olive oil or any other oil. In this case, our arrived in a small hotplate where the server proceeded to help us mix the Potato Hash, Onsen Egg and Chorizo and frying it on the spot. Not gonna lie, the end product reminded me of Char Kway Tiao.

Just like its moniker, Chikin Tsukune is basically charcoal grilled meatballs. Chicken tsukune usually varies from shop to shop, since the recipe for making it is by using up chicken scraps that might otherwise go to waste. Here, the meatballs were pretty huge and arrived super glossy, where its soaked in Sansho Tare that spots a thick viscosity and sweet caramelised flavour. My only qualm were the soft bones mixed in the meatball - it does give it a slight crunch to change up the texture but I personally do not like soft bones.

The Ebi Sriracha features Prawn Tempura with Sriracha Mayo and Tobiko and is the dish that stood out least through out the night. The fact that it's not deshelled also make eating it less enjoyable #firstworldproblem

Chef Angus Wagyu Sando has to be the highlight of the meal (since it's the most expensive one lol) and for good reason. The soft and buttery slab of wagyu beef is packed between 2 lightly toasted/fried slices of bread, topped with caviar before being showered with gold dust. Very boujee but thought it was lacking a little in terms of flavour.", 'date': 'a year ago', 'images': ['https://storage.googleapis.com/synthesis_geos_public/thumbnails/thumb_unavail.jpg']}, {'rating': 4, 'description': 'I had a chance to come here with my girl last month. First impression when I came to Kitty is the decoration, with Japanese style, main color tone is yellow - red - orange, as you can see in the picture. Love the lanterns and the leaves. We chose to sit right at the counter so we could observe bartenders making drinks.

For food, we ordered quite a lot since both of us were so hungry after work. So sorry I forgot to take pictures since I was so hungry. We had:
- Risotto Al Tatufo $34: Just nice for sharing. Love the Black Truffle smell in the Risotto, not too strong.
- Chikin Tsukune $15: Charcoal-grilled Meatballs with Sansho Tare - not bad at all but it is little bit salty for me.
- Iberico Secreto $32: Iberico pork with Sweet Garlic Puree and Raisins, not impressive. I could not recall the flavor of this dish.
- Frog Leg Tempura $24 - super recommend this dish. The frog leg is crispy but not dry, believe me, not dry at all. It is served together with a special chilli sauce that the bartender told me to be careful because it is very spicy. Yet, I can eat spicy food, so it is not a big deal for me :)))))
- Last one is the Gyoza Iberico with X.O. Sauce $15: I like this dish. Perfect seasoning.

Drink:
- Vodka Grey goose - neat
- Sake no Hana $22 - first time trying this mixture so it is a little bit strange for me. Ingredients include: Junmai Sake, St. Germain, Pomegranate, Bubbles
- My girl ordered a drink that is specially made with a special device to create smoky - burning smell and taste for the drink. Quite unique but I am sorry, I cannot remember the name.

I will come back here again to try the rest of the food and beverage menu.

In general
(+)
- Pleasant view, suitable for those who love taking pictures
- Staff are super friendly and supportive
- Food in general is served quite fast
- Have social media such as Facebook and Instagram, official website also. You can have a look at the menu from the official website.
- The place is clean, well maintained, and the furniture is quite new as well.

(-)
- If you are not accustomed to the Clarke Quay area, it will be a little bit difficult for you to find the place.
- Please make reservations from Fri to Sunday because it is very crowded, normal day no need, but recommend booking a table too to have a better experience.', 'date': '10 months ago', 'images': ['https://storage.googleapis.com/synthesis_geos_public/thumbnails/thumb_unavail.jpg']}]

Chinese restaurant serving a pretty good Peking duck which they cooked the left over meat with mee pok thereafter.

Reservations are recommended, as the restaurant does have seats along the walkway. I would not want to be seated outside for my meal if the restaurant is fully booked out.

I would say the delight of the meal is definitely the Peking duck and the noodles fried with the duck. The skin was very crispy and the restaurant wasn‚Äôt stingy when we asked for more spring onion and cucumbers. I would ask the restaurant to increase the portion of the cucumber and spring onion for guests as it was not enough for the number of skin from the duck. The hoisin sauce was delicious and accompanied the duck perfectly. The skin was just a regular egg skin which you can purchase from the grocery stall easily. The steamed fish was very fresh and definitely must applaud the restaurant on the quality of the fish. I do find the stir fried Kai lan quite hard though and least enjoyable of all dishes. I would say the fried mee pok with duck meat was very enjoyable and unique as mee pok is not a dish you would be able to find as a stir fried fish easily. The mango pudding was good and not too sweet. I would not need to add in the evaporated milk as it was good as it came in.

One main issue I found with the dishes is the cracker which came with the duck. It did look overly oily and seemed like the oil wasn‚Äôt drained off.

Service was quite ok. Food was value for money. If you order $100, you can order a Peking duck for $58 which is genius marketing. Most guests would be able to meet $100 easily and would not stop at a chance to get a $58 Peking duck.
